page.text: Nitsch Engineering has prepared this Existing Conditions Traffic Study to review the existing traffic operations for
the proposed redevelopment of the Powder House School Site, located at the southeast corner of the Teele Square
– Broadway at Holland Street at Curtis Street – in Somerville, Massachusetts.
As part of the project, the following roadways and intersections were studied:
Figure 1 depicts the Locus Map of the study area and surrounding roadway network. Figure 2 depicts the Study
Broadway runs in an east-west direction and provides frontage on the north side of the proposed site. In the vicinity
of the site, the roadway is classified as an urban minor arterial. The roadway runs between Interstate 93 in
Somerville and Massachusetts Avenue (Route 2A) in Arlington. Adjacent to Interstate 93 and Massachusetts
Avenue (Route 2A), the roadway is classified as an urban principal arterial.
In the vicinity of the site, the roadway generally contains one (1) travel lane in each direction with sidewalks and
parallel parking available on both sides of the roadway. The posted speed limit along the roadway is 30 miles per
hour (mph). East of the intersection with Holland Street, the land use is primarily residential. West of the
intersection with Holland Street, the land use is primarily commercial with some residential properties. In the
vicinity of the site, the roadway is maintained by the City of Somerville.
Holland Street runs in a north-south direction and provides frontage on the west side of the proposed site. Holland
Street runs between Broadway at its north side to the intersection with Elm Street and Highland Avenue at its south
side and is classified as an urban minor arterial.
In the vicinity of the site, the roadway generally contains one (1) travel lane in each direction with sidewalks and
parallel parking available on both sides of the roadway. The posted speed limit along the roadway is 30 mph. The
land use is primarily residential with some commercial properties. The roadway is maintained by the City of
Broadway and Holland Street intersect to form a three-approach, signalized intersection in the City of Somerville
with Broadway approaching from the east and west with Holland Street intersecting from the south. The
intersection is known as Teele Square. Curtis Street extends from the intersection to the north as a one-way
roadway; therefore, there is no approach to the intersection associated with this roadway. Newbury Street extends
from the intersection to the southwest as a one-way roadway; therefore there is no approach to the intersection
associated with this roadway. A City of Somerville fire station is located just south of Newbury Street on the west
side of Curtis Street. Due to the need for the emergency vehicles to have access to the intersection, the stop line
for the Curtis Street approach is located south of the fire station, creating a wide intersection perimeter. Due to this,
the intersection requires secondary stop lines and signal heads located within the limits of the intersection.

9-foot wide parallel parking spaces in each direction. Holland Street contains shared-
markings in each direction at the approach. The posted speed limit at this approach is 30 mph. Within the limits of
the intersection, a triangle island is present that permits a yield-controlled right turn movement from Curtis Street
From the east, Broadway is approximately 42 feet wide and in each direction contains one (1) 11-foot wide travel

A Level of Service (LOS) analysis is a quantitative assessment of traffic operations at an intersection. Nitsch
Engineering conducted a LOS analysis at the study area intersections using the procedures outlined in the
. The intersections were analyzed using SYNCHRO Version 6
computer software, which conforms to MassDOT requirements. The HCM bases its LOS results on average
delay experienced by vehicles at intersections. The HCM categorizes LOS by letters A through F, with LOS A
representing minimum delays and good service, and LOS F representing significant delays and poor service.
MassDOT considers, LOS A, B, C, and D as acceptable in urban/suburban areas, and LOS E and LOS F as
unacceptable. Table 2 shows the LOS criteria for signalized and un-signalized intersections.

software for roadway and intersection capacity studies and coordinated arterials, which is approved by MassDOT.
